  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Method/Visual_flight_rules_581119/83_36_40">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_schema/so_MLE#Method"/>
    <so:method_name>Visual flight rules</so:method_name>
    <so:textual_span>MVAS</so:textual_span>
    <so:has_sentence_context rdf:resource="https://scholarlyontology.aueb.gr/resources/so_instances/so_MLE#Sentence/581119/83"/>
    <so:description>In aviation, visual flight rules (VFR) is a set of regulations under which a pilot operates an aircraft in weather conditions generally clear enough to allow the pilot to see where the aircraft is going. Specifically, the weather must be better than basic VFR weather minima, i.e., in visual meteorological conditions (VMC), as specified in the rules of the relevant aviation authority.</so:description>
    <so:wikipedia_url>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=32698</so:wikipedia_url>
  </rdf:Description>
